  <p>The page types are:</p>
  <p>LINKS HERE</p>
  <h4>Sitemap as family tree</h4>
  <p>We talk about pages higher up in the hierarchy being ‘parents’ of the pages immediately below them. For example, a supermarket may have the following hierarchy:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>‘Fresh food’ is the parent page of ‘Fruit’ and ‘Vegetables’</li>
    <li>‘Vegetables’ is the parent page of ‘Broccoli’, ‘New potatoes’ and ‘Mushrooms’</li>
    <li>‘Broccoli’, ‘New potatoes’ and ‘Mushrooms’ are child pages of ‘Vegetables’</li>
    <li>‘Broccoli’, ‘New potatoes’ and ‘Mushrooms’ are sibling pages</li>
    <li>‘Lemons’, ‘Oranges’ and ‘Grapefruit’ are also sibling pages</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This matters when it comes to talking about navigation structures:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A parent page must contain links to all its child pages</li>
    <li>A child page must provide a link to its parent page</li>
    <li>A page must provide links to all its siblings</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This ensures that no pages are ‘orphaned’ by not being available via navigation. It also ensures that users can always find ‘nearby’ content to continue their journey.</p>
  <p>Within the navigation system:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Hub pages are ‘parent’ pages. They contain links to all their ‘child’ pages (which can be hub pages and/or content pages)</li>
    <li>Breadcrumbs on all pages provide links to parent pages. (On mobile, just the immediate parent. On desktop, all grandparents are there too.)</li>
    <li>Bottom navigation on content pages pages provides links to both parent and sibling pages</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Use IA page templates and components</h3>
  <h4>Hub pages</h4>
  <p>Hub pages are designed to do one thing well: to route people to the content they need. Not to provide that content. They provide consistent navigation structures to allow users to browse to their destination, discover content they didn’t know they needed and re-find information without getting lost. Users can scan, select and move on quickly.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>They show users where they are and where else they might go</li>
    <li>They showcase all content for any given topic or sub-topic</li>
    <li>They allow you to promote up to three ‘top tasks’ for your topic, to provide shortcuts to popular content that would otherwise be ‘buried’ in your site map hierarchy</li>
    <li>They showcase related links for any given topic or sub-topic - content that users interested in your topic may find useful, but isn’t contained within your content. For example, treatments for a condition or services associated with a healthy living topic.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Each ‘parent’ page in your site map represents a ‘hub’ page in your prototype. Your hub page will list all the child pages of the parent page. These child pages can be a mix of further hubs and/or content pages. We call these ‘canonical’ links, as they represent the single home of any one piece of content. This is in contrast to related links, which reference related content elsewhere in the sitemap.</p>
  <p>There are two different hub page templates - the main topic hub and the sub topic hub. This allows the design to change as users move through the content. (Helping users understand they’ve ‘moved’).</p>
  <p>Main topic hubs are used for larger groups of content, for example a group of conditions like Diabetes or a group of medicines like Antihistamines. Individual conditions or medicines are served by sub topic hubs.</p>
  <h5>Level 1 Hub</h5>
  <p>Use for larger groups of content.</p>
  <p>Components:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Breadcrumbs (link to parent pages)</li>
    <li>Page title and intro text (to help users to ascertain if they are in the right place)</li>
    <li>‘Top tasks’ (optional links to up to 3 pages that are high priority tasks for users. They must be grandchild or great-grandchild links from within the topic, not related links from elsewhere)</li>
    <li>Canon links (to all child pages, including intro text to help users choose)</li>
    <li>Related links</li>
    <li>External links - to related content elsewhere on the internet</li>
  </ul>
  <h5>Level 2 hub</h5>
  <p>Use for smaller groups of content such as sub-topics under a main topic hub.</p>
  <p>Components:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Breadcrumbs (link to parent pages)</li>
    <li>Page title and optional intro text (to help users to ascertain if they are in the right place)</li>
    <li>Canon links (to all child pages)</li>
    <li>Related links</li>
    <li>External links - to related content elsewhere on the internet</li>
  </ul>
  <h5>Content pages</h5>
  <p>Our content pages are designed to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Allow users to ascertain if they are in the right place, and correct themselves if not</li>
    <li>Read the content</li>   
    <li>Facilitate the discovery of additional content within the topic</li>
    <li>Ensure there are no ‘dead ends’ if they want to continue their journey</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Very long pages are bad for accessibility.</p>
  <p>Components:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Breadcrumbs (link to parent pages)</li>
    <li>Page title (to help users to ascertain if they are in the right place)</li>
    <li>Sideways navigation (to link to the parent page and all sibling pages)</li>
  </ul>
  <h4>Test and iterate</h4>
  <p>Your researcher can run first-click tests and usability tests to evaluate your prototype.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>First-click tests are run remotely to test the IA and visual hierarchy together. Your IA may work well in tree tests, but can people still find what they need in the context of the rest of the website? First-click tests show users an image of your hub page and ask them where they would click to complete common tasks.</li>
    <li>You can run usability tests that evaluate whether users are able to find your content and move around it, as well as whether the content itself meets user needs. You can evaluate your new hubs and content pages against the site-wide user needs.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 8: Plan how to move into Beta</h2>
  <p>Throughout the ideation phase and the steps within, it is likely you have iterated and had more than one viable option for how to progress the work. This step is about reflecting on and applying your learnings to define how the team progresses with the work and effectively selects one way forwards.</p>
  <h3>UI design and iteration<h3>
  <p>Decide the most viable designs and conduct the following research methods:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Tree test</li>
    <li>First click tests</li>
  </ol>
  <p>This will tell you how the designs need to be changed and whether they meet your users' mental models and top tasks.</p>
  <p>It may be useful at this point to have a full working prototype of your proposed IA and navigation changes.</p>

